description.plain:
“Bitter” is a is the debut official single taken from FLETCHER’s sophomore EP with Capital Records, “The S(ex) Tapes”. The song was originally not planned to be released, but due to fan requests FLETCHER released it. “Bitter” was written with and produced by Australian producer Kito.

The song was first played in an episode of the television series The L Word, on January 12th, 2020, and was released several months later on May 13th. https://twitter.com/IamKier/status/1216472425895849985?s=20

annotations: It’s like you finally get a text back and it’s just your mom

This line could refer to a real-life incident. Cari has admitted that she has sent racy or flirty texts to her mom by accident on multiple occasions:

I was trying to flirt with somebody and say something cute and I sent it to my mom. I wasn’t sending a nude, I was just sending a cute picture. Because I knew that I also had to text my mom and she sends me this whole thing back.
It’s like I don’t give a fuck... yeah, I do
Fletcher wants to pretend she doesn’t care about the subject’s life anymore and is over the relationship. However, she doubles-down and admits she is still sensitive about her ex.
That you threw out all our furniture and pictures?
Refers to the subject and speaker’s relationship ending and their physical seperation. ‘Threw,’ describes the speaker’s anger at the abrupt end.

description.plain:
“Becky’s So Hot” was first teased on various snippets posted to FLETCHER’s TikTok account. In these teaser snippets, Becky’s name was initially censored, leading to fan speculation about the subject of the song.

When asked who the song was about, FLETCHER has been quoted saying that she used the name as a pop trope:

 I wasn’t setting out to create something that needed to be confirmed or speculated about. I just jumped at the opportunity to use a name that’s been a trope for decades.

Fans have speculated that the song is directed towards ex-girlfriend Shannon Beveridge’s current girlfriend Becky Missal. FLETCHER and Shannon’s break-up inspired The S(ex) Tapes – EP which was recorded during their quarantine during COVID-19, and Beveridge shot, directed and starred in music videos for the EP.

Although Beveridge initially distanced herself from the song, the pair has since put out limited edition t-shirts inspired by these lyrics.

annotations: Makes me wanna hit her when I see her
The singer is surprised by her unexpected feelings, demonstrated in the double meaning of “hit” — to physically strike or to hit someone up.
Fine, okay, I’ll say, I went and stalked her

FLETCHER revealed in an interview with Zane Lowe that she stalked her ex-girlfriend’s new girlfriend on Instagram and accidentally liked a picture. Instead of immediately unliking, she said:

I accidentally liked it. I kept it, because … you just have to lean in and … own the fact that yeah I was creeping.
’Cause Becky’s so hot in your vintage t-shirt

Although Cari has not publicly acknowledged who the Becky in the song is, fans have speculated that it must be Cari’s ex Shannon Beveridge’s new girlfriend Becky Missal.

She wore a t-shirt that fits the song’s description on Instagram on February 21, 2020.



There is also one of Shannon wearing a similarly themed t-shirt from February 29th 2019.

As the song blew up on TikTok, Beveridge responded:

This is not PR that I am a part of … no one asked permission.

However, a while later, Missal and Beveridge seemed to confirm the song was about their romance by putting out limited edition t-shirts for charity:

Cari responded:

Look, I think it’s badass that somebody went and claimed it for themselves and confirmed that that is who they are, right? But like I said, songwriters have been using Becky for a long time.

annotations: I’m not the best at breakin’ up

Cari has been honest about her codependency issues, saying:

I’ve been in consistent relationships since I was twelve. I never really developed the appropriate coping mechanisms to dealing with anxiety by myself. I’ve always made somebody else my rock. […] Both people don’t want to let each other go, ‘cause how do you let something special go?

This led to her quarantining with her ex in 2020 and making The S(ex) Tapes together, a project about that same ex. The pair had been in an on-and-off relationship for four years.

In “I Think I’m Growing?,” Cari reflects on these problems she faces:

I saw all the parts I didn’t like
So insecure, so quick to fight
I didn’t know I was so co-dependent
I didn’t know I had so much resentment
So many girl-of my-dreams
FLETCHER references the name of the album here and reveals the double meaning behind the album name – where the girl of her dreams refers to herself, and also refers to the object of her affection.

this song is about wishing you could undo last night, or wishing you could unlove the person that completely and utterly broke your heart.

it’s like a page ripped out of my diary.

annotations:
Been through every emotion
 Right now, I’m sad and broken

Self love is something that I really struggle with and did. I still do, and after that breakup I really did and like that is such a journey in and of itself and I think that you can’t love somebody else if you don’t love yourself and you don’t respect yourself. I didn’t respect myself in that situation. After I got out of it, I like really, had that perspective and aside from just going out and partying, I think you really just have to like take the time to kind of, as cheesy as it sounds, but do like a self dive and like check yourself. Am I good? And like that answer for me was no and I think it’s just I … You gotta get a therapist. That’s step number one, my therapist is the greatest person in the entire world because she listens to all of my bullshit and helps me feel a little less insane and helps me put like feelings to the … I mean words to the things that I’m feeling and I think that, that’s something that’s really important and just, you know, doing the things that you love and that you’re really passionate about and finding your creativity and surrounding yourself with the people that make you feel like the best you. It’s such a roller coaster of emotions. Like one day you’ll be totally fine and be like, “I can do this, I’ve got this.” And you feel really good and good about yourself and like what you’ve got going on in your life and where you’re kind of at and then the next you’re just like curled up in a ball on the bathroom floor of your shower or whatever, or crying in a stall in like a restaurant or a bar.

Oh, I’m hungry and wasted and my hands are shaking
 I shouldn’t be cooking, but spilling hot water
 It still doesn’t burn as much as the thought of you

My go-to drunk food is always nachos. Like literally it doesn’t matter what time it is, come home, throw some Tostitos on a plate, a little shredded cheese, pop it in the microwave, a little sour cream/salsa dipping action is where it’s at. Nothing better. But, the amount of times that I’ve come home and cooked a bunch of food drunk and then woke up in the morning and it’s like, left stuff out, it’s bad, have to throw it out, can’t use it anymore.

Is it weird if I come over?
 I want to, but I know that she’s around
It’s about like I really wanna see you, can I just come over, but I feel like you’re probably … You might be with somebody else.

I’m afraid to turn the lights on
 I don’t wanna face this rebound

It’s like of open to interpretation, it could be your own rebound that you don’t wanna literally turn the lights on and look at and just be like, “You were a 10 last night. Something happened and you’re now not. And either am I and why is my mascara, where are we, okay.” That and also just the fact you know that your ex or whatever, the person you’re feeling all these things for, that you’re trying to get over is like out sleeping or doing whatever with whoever. It’s just that sick feeling that you wake up in the morning and you’re like, “What did they do last night?” And like, “It doesn’t matter, I have no control over it and I shouldn’t care, but I do.” It’s that.

But some things you can’t undo
 And one of them’s you

There’s always things that you’re gonna do that you wish you could back in time and change and undo them, and it is, it’s always the things that you feel the worst about that you wish you could undo. But, it builds character. It makes you who you are, it teaches you a lesson. You learn from it, you grow from it, and like, I think it’s really hard to see that lesson when you’re in the thick of it. But once you get some perspective, and are able to sort of see these a little but more clearly, it makes a hell of a lot more sense. And, I think, just really important to your journey. I would never go back and undo the relationship, because it taught me so much about myself that I didn’t know that I needed to know, that has since effected, like, the way that I have been in relationships and situations post that.

I wish I could un-kiss the room full of strangers
 So I could un-spite you, un-lose my temper

I mean, I think when you break up with somebody, everybody sort of goes through like a different healing process through it, and sometimes you end up looking for attention right after, you know? And you try to convince yourself that you’re fine and like you wanna feel wanted. And hot and like, feel like you’re having fun and so, maybe you go out and kiss a bunch of strangers. But like, no matter what you do, they’re still not that one person. And that’s like such a sad realization at the end of the night, and I think we, you know, at times we end up like looking for that attention, not necessarily in the best place.

Wish I could get a little un-drunk so I could un-call you
 At 5 in the morning, I would un-fuck you
 But some things you can’t undo

I think it’s so impossible to stop talking to an ex or somebody that you really loved at one time, especially if you’re still in love with them, and they like really hurt you, and you start finding excuses for all of the things that they did. And the stuff that they put you through. And then you also start to like, well, what did I do, that made them do this? And it’s manipulative, and it’s abusive to yourself and it’s honestly, like a drug. Like, love is such a drug, we actually, our brains release the same chemicals as a drug addict that’s going through a withdrawal. Learned that in a podcast, recently. Which is actually like we experience the same physical, biological reaction to a heartbreak, which is so crazy to me, but also at the same time, it’s not, because you literally are having withdraws from a person that you spent every waking second with, and knew every thought of, and what they were thinking, and what made them tick, and what they loved and what they hated. And to go from being so involved with somebody on such an intimate level, to then, all of a sudden, then them being a complete stranger and having no part of your life, is like a concept that will never make sense to me. And probably to anyone, and there’s nothing like that pain.

Honestly, this party’s over
 Everyone here shoulda gone home

The feeling that I really wanted to capture, that I’ve had personally, so many times and I’m sure somebody else has had, that feeling where you’re leaving, after the after party’s over, and you’re leaving or you’re walking home or you’re in your cab or your Uber, or whatever, by yourself, and there’s nothing left to distract you, no like substance, alcohol, like fling or flirt or crush or anything, and you’re literally just by yourself with your drunken thoughts, swirling around in your head and there’s nothing left to distract you from that one person that just fucked you up and broke your heart. And that you just can’t really seem to get over, and that was, that moment for me, that I had so many times, after that breakup, and I just wanted to capture that pain, that you could try to cover it up with as much shit as you possibly could, but it’s like a fucking virus, that keeps on coming back.
Like the bottles on the floor, but I’m too buzzed to clean ’em up

Amy Allen and I wrote the bridge a few months after we started the song w/ Tim and Jeremy. This lyric just flowed out of us, and really makes the song come full-circle for me. It’s after you’ve hosted a pregame or a party or something like that and everybody’s gone and the only thing that’s left are the wounded soldiers.  You don’t want to clean them up and they’re sad. Like the bottles are sad sitting there when there’s like no life left at the party and it’s just you. You’re just like, “I don’t even care. I don’t even want to touch this stuff. I just feel terrible.” So, it’s just about, yeah, it’s about that feeling that you have at the end of the night when you’re reflecting on a lot of things drunk.  It doesn’t ever really make complete sense and it’s always way more emotional. The tears flow way harder when you’re wasted.

Wish I could get a little un-drunk so I could un-call you
 At 5 in the morning, I would un-fuck you

People have the shortest attention span, and so I’m like, I have to say “unfuck” within the first 7 seconds, otherwise people are gonna be like, next, who cares, what? And so, and also it’s just like if I heard a song that says I wish I could unfuck you, I’d be like what is this, ‘cause like, same.

annotations: Sipped her like an Old Fashioned

This line was inspired by a conversation Fletcher had with Taylor Swift at her 2019 birthday party, during which Fletcher asked Taylor what she was drinking.

I went to her birthday party and she was drinking an old fashioned. And I asked her, “What’s that drink?” And she’s like, “it’s an old fashioned” and I was like and she was like—it’s a man’s drink and I was like you’re the fucking man. That interaction is the reason why in ”Girls Girls Girls" I put “sipped her like an old fashioned” because I thought it was so hot that Taylor Swift was drinking a fucking old fashioned. I need to tell her she inspired that lyric. So “sipped her like an old fashioned” came from our president, Taylor Swift.

annotations:
To the changes and the traumas
 I was keepin’ in a closet

These lines are a reference to the common expression “skeleton in the closet”, which means past memories or experiences that one wants to keep hidden from everyone. However, it also has a more literal meaning, where the “traumas” that FLETCHER was “keepin' in the closet” include her struggles with being closeted and coming to terms with her sexuality.
